<br>
It makes me very happy to see that others on this server feel the same way, and those that have opposing views are very polite about it.  If any of you see me in-game, please feel free to say hello (my I.D. here is my 'toon's name also).  Thanks again, keep the opinions coming &amp; see you on the inside! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/unydiaywalmoriel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nydia Ywalmoriel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(7/30/02 1:06:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2933.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why the powergaming mindset?</span><hr size=1> Dear Twosheds:<br>
<br>
I think part of what you are encountering on A Ro has to do with the fact that this is a particularly 'mature' server, and that you came to this game when it was already well over 2 years old.  I started playing in Jan 2001, and even then there were a lot of folks who were heavily twinked out and/or mainly interested in powerlevelling up to where the 'real' game was with the folks post level 50.  Some of the first people I hooked up with in that game had that mindset, and I found it very irritating when they would try to give me stuff or drag me someplace where we would stand in one place and kill mobs while some L 50 druid or enchanter would babysit us.  Talk about boring!  So Faervas and I resolved that we weren't going to let the game be 'ruined' for us, and made an effort to find other people who were also new to the game to play with, or who were at least willing to explore, and make messy mistakes in, exotic places.  A year and a half later, we have friends in our little resultant guild with mains from level 13-55; and while we have crawled at least part of all of the old world dungeons, most of the newer ones in our level range, and are about to take our first all guild group to Sebilis, we have mains who are just now doing Unrest and Najena, so we try very hard to let those who are just starting to learn the game, or are very casual players, enjoy the game at their own pace.  <br>
<br>
I personally don't get, either, people who 'rush' the levelling/item acquisition process; in my mind, they are only cheating themselves out of a big part of the joy of the game.  It *does* suck some when you are in small guild and you can't offer your friends much other than a good time because the item economy in the game is so screwed up.  In that regard the Luclin Twilight quests have been a godsend, as they are something that most of our folks can help with, and that we get a sense of accomplishment (and some spiffy, unique stuff!) out of doing.   But some folks are always going to have the linear, 'beat the game' kind of mindset, even in a very open-ended game like EQ, and well, all I can say is 'different strokes for different folks...<br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
Nydia Ywalmoriel<br>
Autonomous Collective<br>
<br>
P.S.  Some of the best times I have ever had in the game have been in Runnyeye, especially just post-revamp. <br>
