Autonomous Collective <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/unydiaywalmoriel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nydia Ywalmoriel</A> at: 8/4/02 10:45:13 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/usaintsaens.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saintsaens</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Wanderer</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(8/5/02 1:11:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2933.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why the powergaming mindset?</span><hr size=1> Well, on TZ, most people were required to raid with their prospective guildmates, which I assume is the custom here as well.  My problem is, I cannot stand not being in a guild.  I miss guildchat, and I miss having people to talk to (otherwise I bug my /friends list constantly, just ask Narf :)).<br>
<br>
I also don't see the point of soloing to 60, but then again this is coming from my personal beliefs.  If I am forced to solo, I kill 2 mobs and am bored almost to tears.  I much prefer being in a group or at the very least having a partner to have someone to talk to than being by myself medding for 10 minutes.  Also I find when you're in a good group, exp seems to flow faster, especially if you're taking out red and yellow mobs with ease.<br>
<br>
Again, I don't see how large scale raids can be &quot;uninteresting,&quot; but that's probably the powergamer in me talking.  To me, the game is about helping myself and my guildmates kill high end mobs, and the challenge involved in getting quests done or zones cleared.  I know there's lots of lag on raids, and not everyone walks away from a raid with something, but there's the fact that I'm helping others that makes a raid interesting for me.<br>
<br>
Saintsaens <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/unydiaywalmoriel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nydia Ywalmoriel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(8/5/02 4:03:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2933.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why the powergaming mindset?</span><hr size=1> Personally, I don't like soloing either, except occasionally to test my limits; as an enchanter, small groups are where the most 'fun' and action is, imho.  But I do know people who largely soloed their way to 60; and some are actually competent players.  And while I respect the organization and the effort that goes into large target raids, as well as what they are able to accomplish, it's just not my scene (one man's meat being another man's poison, and all).  If it can be done with 3 groups or less (4 being tops for me, after that it just starts to feel like a mob scene, not to mention being overkill for most of the encounters I participate in), I'm all for it; and you'd be surprised what you can do with 15 people in mostly crap gear with an average level of 55, if you have folks who are flexible and on the ball.  My own little guild's raids are usually even smaller, averaging 8 peeps of avg level 46 these days, but we are just starting to get to the high end Kunark dungeons (worked Seb and HS keys this week, Faer and I made our first trip to HS), and into Kael arena, which is very exciting for us.  We've completed several Twilight quest armor pieces for every sub-50 main in the guild (which have unique graphics, our 21st level cleric gets asked all the time about his violet armor, which belonged to the late Eanaman), and our Ranger made her Rallic pack tonight <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.